export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>This chapter is the report's conscience: the strongest case against AI-for-materials, made before any critic has to make it, in the field's own primary sources — re-analyses, failed replications, protocols, corrections, misconduct findings. Section 20.1 is the register, with each episode's standing as of 2026-07-17, the meta-objections, and an audit of my own nine classes. Section 20.2 converts skepticism into procedure; §20.3 states what would change my mind.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s20-1-1", "html": "<p>Between 2019 and 2026 the field produced two fabrications, one artifact, one collapsed literature, and three flagship overstatements — and corrected all seven itself, in peer-reviewed rebuttal, protocol reform, and journal action. Table 20.1 gives each claim as it was made.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 20.1 — The counter-narrative register (statuses as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Claim (as made)</th>\n<th>Venue / year</th>\n<th>Counter-evidence</th>\n<th>Resolution status as of 2026-07-17</th>\n<th>Lesson for this venture</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>An autonomous laboratory &quot;realized 41 novel compounds from a set of 58 targets&quot; in 17 days <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"28\">[28]</sup></td>\n<td>Nature 2023 (A-Lab)</td>\n<td>Automated Rietveld refinement and disorder-handling errors; &quot;no new materials have been discovered in that work&quot; (Leeman, Schoop, Palgrave et al.) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup></td>\n<td>Author Correction of 19 January 2026 (Nature 650:E1) walks back the novelty claims — the corrected title drops &quot;novel&quot;; the robotics methodology stands <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"28\">[28]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup></td>\n<td>The weak link was automated characterization, not the AI: no compound leaves my lab claimed without an independent diffraction audit</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2.2 million crystals, 381,000 &quot;newly discovered stable materials&quot; (GNoME)</td>\n<td>Nature 2023</td>\n<td>&quot;Scant evidence&quot; of compounds passing a novelty–credibility–utility trifecta (Cheetham &amp; Seshadri) — their argument, widely reported as a single-digit-percent survival share <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"30\">[30]</sup></td>\n<td>Contested: DeepMind &quot;stand[s] by all claims,&quot; citing 736 structures since synthesized in the literature <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"216\">[216]</sup>; no full-list third-party novelty audit exists</td>\n<td>Prediction volume is not discovery; the unit of account is one novel, credible, useful material</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>LK-99: room-temperature, ambient-pressure superconductivity</td>\n<td>arXiv + social media, 2023</td>\n<td>More than 15 failed replications; floating-zone single crystals are semiconducting; the resistivity drop traces to a Cu<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>S impurity transition near 104 °C <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"143\">[143]</sup></td>\n<td>Closed: artifact, not superconductivity — error, not fraud</td>\n<td>Replication velocity is now weeks; a cheap simulation-plus-characterization screen kills artifact claims before they consume attention</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Room-temperature superconductivity, twice: CSH at 288 K (~155 GPa); N-doped lutetium hydride at 294 K near-ambient (Dias)</td>\n<td>Nature 2020; Nature 2023 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"141\">[141]</sup></td>\n<td>Failed replications; 8 of 11 co-authors requested retraction of the second paper; a university investigation found &quot;falsification, fabrication, and/or plagiarism of data, images, and text&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"114\">[114]</sup></td>\n<td>Both papers retracted (2022; 2023); roughly five papers retracted in total, the senior author dismissed, a $17M startup with no reproducible result <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"114\">[114]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"142\">[142]</sup></td>\n<td>Fabrication survives only where raw data is unauditable; my numbers ship with deposited data, not descriptions of data</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&quot;AI-assisted researchers discover 44% more materials&quot; (+39% patent filings, +17% product innovation)</td>\n<td>MIT working paper (arXiv), 2024 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup></td>\n<td>Fabricated: MIT declared &quot;no confidence in the provenance, reliability or validity of the data&quot;; the author departed <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup></td>\n<td>Disowned in May 2025 and to be &quot;withdrawn from public discourse&quot; — after citation by Nature, the Wall Street Journal, the US Congress, the ECB, and an EU Commissioner <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup></td>\n<td>Never quote a second-hand productivity statistic; every number in my pitch must be auditable to its source</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dozens of DFT-guided electrochemical N<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>-reduction catalysts &quot;synthesize ammonia at ambient conditions&quot;</td>\n<td>Multiple journals, 2016–2019</td>\n<td>Contamination-driven false positives; a quantitative isotope protocol (Andersen et al.) exposed the class <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"234\">[234]</sup></td>\n<td>Collapsed: the isotope protocol is now mandatory across the subfield; the earlier claims are disbelieved <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"234\">[234]</sup></td>\n<td>A computed activity map is not an experiment; measurement protocols precede pipelines</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ML classifiers can pick water-stable MOFs for capture duty (83%/71% test accuracy)</td>\n<td>Nat. Mach. Intell. 2020 (Batra); JACS 2024 (WS24) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"339\">[339]</sup></td>\n<td>Accuracy collapses under metal- and topology-grouped splits — an &quot;optimism gap&quot;; apparent cross-dataset transfer partly duplicate structures <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"341\">[341]</sup>; MOF-74's hydrolysis driving force exceeds ZIFs' by 200–250 kJ/mol per metal center (≈2.1–2.6 eV; 96.485 kJ/mol = 1 eV), so room-temperature persistence masquerades as stability <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup></td>\n<td>Open: classifiers demoted from prediction to triage; the field's flagship inventor says &quot;there's a lot of hype versus reality&quot;; one MOF (CALF-20) has reached industrial service <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"330\">[330]</sup></td>\n<td>Predict survival in water, not uptake; own the thermodynamic stability labels before claiming the axis</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The register is not one failure mode but four: over-reading (rows one and two — real pipelines whose claims outran their characterization); artifact and fabrication (rows three to five); protocol failure (row six — a subfield optimizing an observable no one had made measurable); and label failure (row seven — honest models trained on honest-but-wrong labels, the quietest case and the one most relevant here). Two facts matter more than any row: not one episode was caught by its authors' internal validation — every correction arrived from outside, within one to three years — and the corrections held. Error-correction in this field is external, adversarial, and effective: a venture that internalizes it first converts the field's scarcest asset into its moat; one that does not will appear in someone else's register.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s20-1-2", "html": "<p><strong>The hype cycle is structural.</strong> The amplification chain that carried a fabricated 44% productivity figure to Nature, Congress, and an EU Commissioner <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup> rewards volume headlines, and the register's first two rows show the field supplying them. <strong>Error bars are worse than admitted — by the field's own benchmarks.</strong> OC20's energy MAE plateaued near 0.2 eV for two years against a 0.1 eV target <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup>; five foundation potentials post barrier MAEs of 0.310–0.349 eV across 574 DFT-NEB paths, 4–6× the ~60 meV DFT floor <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup>; universal force fields average 5.2% density error versus their own labels' 2.5%, with elastic errors to 188.6% <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"92\">[92]</sup>; MS25 finds a 0.74 ± 0.06 eV barrier error at ~0.2 meV/atom energy error (±0.06 eV ≈ 1 kcal/mol, a 10× rate error at 300 K) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>. <strong>Stability is the graveyard of predictions.</strong> A December 2025 meta-analysis calls 0.3–0.5 eV a conservative uncertainty for one adsorption energy and urges a pivot to &quot;synthesizability, stability, lifetime or affordability&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"44\">[44]</sup>; hydrolysis dooms frameworks whose kinetic persistence the classifiers called stable <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup>. <strong>Policy timing is luck.</strong> DOE terminated $2.2B of hydrogen-hub funding in October 2025 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"237\">[237]</sup>; I treat every program as a demand signal, none as a forecast (§11.5, §16).</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s20-1-3", "html": "<p>The register buys credibility only if it turns inward: six of my nine classes carry named overhype risk. <strong>Perovskites — durability.</strong> Product warranties run 10 years against silicon's 25–30, a 45-day outdoor test is the durability proof point, and certified records sit on roughly 0.3% of manufacturing capacity <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"346\">[346]</sup>; I make no tandem-lifetime claim until the tools can predict lifetime (§12.4). <strong>MOFs — water.</strong> The register's seventh row is my own chosen class; my dataset bet sits on the field's weakest labels (§11.4). <strong>β-Ga<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>O<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span> — thermal.</strong> An anisotropic ~9.5–29 W/m·K conductivity — one to two orders below GaN and SiC — falls &quot;short for effective heat dissipation&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"369\">[369]</sup>; the field concedes a thermally limited device plateau (§12.4). <strong>Solid-state batteries — timelines.</strong> Penetration in 2025 rounds to zero, Hyundai–Kia slipped toward 2030, and the class has absorbed a short-seller report and a securities class action <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"215\">[215]</sup>; my planning basis is the slow curve (§7.4). <strong>Hydrides — pressure practicality.</strong> Every verified record requires megabar pressures — H<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>S at 155 GPa, LaH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span> higher still <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"123\">[123]</sup> — and YH<span class=\"math\">$_{10}$</span>, predicted at 305–326 K in 2017, has never been synthesized, with re-estimates near 267 K <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"127\">[127]</sup> (§4.4). <strong>Refractory HEAs — room-temperature brittleness.</strong> The entropy premise failed quantitative testing, and &quot;after decades of efforts… refractory alloys are still unable to replace nickel-based superalloys&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"200\">[200]</sup> (§6.4). The pattern is not incidental: error, value, and hype concentrate in the same places. Each class chapter's counter-narrative is load-bearing in my planning, not decorative.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s20-2", "html": "<p>Skepticism that does not change procedure is posture. Six commitments govern every claim this venture makes — mine to keep or to break.</p>\n<p><strong>First, observable-first validation on every claim.</strong> My rule: no energy-or-force error headlines a result. Every model is validated on the observable it must predict — density, barrier, phonon, elastic constant — because the field's own suites show low energy errors coexisting with unusable observables <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"92\">[92]</sup>. A number ships with its observable error bar or not at all.</p>\n<p><strong>Second, uncertainty quantification on every MD observable.</strong> Misspecification-aware UQ now bounds a foundation model's errors across the Materials Project <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"93\">[93]</sup>; where that machinery is too heavy, ensemble disagreement is my floor. If I cannot compute the error bar, the simulation does not ship.</p>\n<p><strong>Third, experiment-anchored residual correction.</strong> My correction loops close on measurement, not on labels: an experimental observable detects the pathology — EXAFS exposed a CHGNet softening that energy errors hid — a micro-dose of DFT corrects it (~100 frames to DFT-level spectra), and experiment re-validates <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"87\">[87]</sup>. Where a linear correction suffices, I take it first: per-element residuals fitted to experiment put PBE formation energies at MAD 0.096 eV/atom, versus r2SCAN's 0.082 at five times the cost <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"89\">[89]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Fourth, open benchmark participation.</strong> Compliant-track Matbench Discovery submissions <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"97\">[97]</sup> and OpenKIM deposits with passing Verification Checks <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"115\">[115]</sup> precede any public claim; third parties check the work without trusting me.</p>\n<p><strong>Fifth, prospective validation with small candidate counts.</strong> My claims are named candidates — single digits to dozens — synthesized and characterized by independent partners, outcomes published either way. There will never be an &quot;N-million materials&quot; announcement from this lab; the register's first three rows are the reason, and the finding that a flagship generative model partly predicts its own training set is the reminder <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"28\">[28]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"30\">[30]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"113\">[113]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Sixth, conflict disclosure, starting with this report.</strong> Single-source figures carry inline hedges, and I restate the ones touching this chapter: the A-Lab correction's exact day rests on secondary accounts (the journal record is issue-dated February) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup>; the GNoME single-digit survival share is the critics' characterization, not a census <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"30\">[30]</sup>. My funding and partnership interests (Chapters 16–19) are disclosed wherever they could color a judgment.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s20-3", "html": "<p>A position paper that cannot state its falsifiers is marketing. Three claims carry this report; each gets a kill condition. <strong>The inherited floor</strong> (Chapter 3) falls if a model trained on PBE-class labels — no fidelity escalation, no experiment anchoring — matches experimental adsorption energies to ≤0.1 eV on a chemically held-out set, or closes to ≤2–3% density error on an external suite. Current readings: a two-year plateau at 0.2 eV <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup>, 5.2% on density <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"92\">[92]</sup>, 0.310–0.349 eV on barriers <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup>. Until they move, the floor stands. <strong>The level playing field</strong> (Chapter 2) falls the day any player — platform, startup, or national program — publicly closes a discovery-to-qualified-part loop in one of the nine classes. As of 2026-07-17 none has; the register shows audits, not loops. <strong>The validation-first wedge</strong> (Chapters 3, 19) falls if database-scale predictions convert into independently audited novel materials faster than small prospective funnels. The strongest counter-evidence today is the 736 GNoME structures synthesized in the independent literature <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"216\">[216]</sup>; if a third-party audit confirms novelty and utility at that scale, I will record the concession in this chapter's successor.</p>\n<p>Until then, the burden of proof sits where this chapter puts it: on anyone claiming discovery without prospective experimental validation — including this author. Chapter 21 turns to a different ledger: the execution risks that remain even when the epistemics are honest.</p>\n" },
]
